docs.abstract: The company, the world’s largest handset maker, said it would postpone the release of the foldable smartphone after reports that the device was malfunctioning.
docs.snippet: The company, the world’s largest handset maker, said it would postpone the release of the foldable smartphone after reports that the device was malfunctioning.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — For the past decade, smartphones have had practically the same design: a rectangular slab with a touch screen. That’s why gadget enthusiasts were eagerly awaiting the release this week of Samsung’s Galaxy Fold, a smartphone that could be folded or unfolded to decrease or increase its screen size.

headline.main: Samsung Postpones Rollout of Galaxy Fold
headline.print_headline: Amid Glitches, Samsung Puts Off Release of Galaxy Fold

byline.original: By Brian X. Chen and Raymond Zhong

docs.abstract: The scandal-plagued bank could go a long way to help federal employees who aren’t being paid during the shutdown. Why hasn’t it done more?

docs.lead_paragraph: Wells Fargo says it wants to make things right with the American public. After years of cheating its customers, the bank has a golden opportunity to make good on its promises.

headline.main: Wells Fargo Should Be More Generous With Federal Workers.

docs.abstract: The two sides made progress in identifying the issues between them, setting the stage for potential talks with top leaders from both countries.

docs.abstract: While a federal judge ruled that the actress’s claims of sexual harassment do not fall within the scope of a state statute, he allowed claims of defamation and unfair business practices to proceed.

docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — A federal judge dismissed part of Ashley Judd’s multipronged lawsuit against Harvey Weinstein on Wednesday, ruling that her allegations of sexual harassment do not fall within the scope of a California statute.

headline.main: Judge Dismisses Part of Ashley Judd’s Lawsuit Against Harvey Weinstein

docs.abstract: The number of people 60 and over is growing. So airports and hotels are beginning to look at design changes to help them.
docs.snippet: The number of people 60 and over is growing. So airports and hotels are beginning to look at design changes to help them.
docs.lead_paragraph: Samantha Flores was having a tough time getting through the airport. The signs were hard to see, the announcements were hard to hear and the people rushing by made her feel unsteady on her stiffened knees. Finally, with relief, she made her way to a bench to sit down, catch her breath and take off her “age simulation suit.”

headline.main: More Benches, Special Goggles: Taking Steps to Assist Older Travelers

docs.abstract: American, Delta and United are among the carriers planning to allow passengers to choose something other than ‘male’ or ‘female’ when buying their tickets.

docs.lead_paragraph: Air travelers who want to will soon be able to choose a gender option other than “male” or “female” when buying their tickets.

headline.main: U.S. Airlines to Offer New Gender Options for Non-Binary Passengers

docs.abstract: A federal judge said the Department of Education had changed its policies without proper notice, throwing the lives of the student-loan borrowers into chaos.
docs.snippet: A federal judge said the Department of Education had changed its policies without proper notice, throwing the lives of the student-loan borrowers into chaos.
docs.lead_paragraph: Three student loan borrowers scored a major victory against the Department of Education on Friday, when a federal judge laid the groundwork for a reversal of the department’s determination that their employers were not eligible for the government’s public service loan forgiveness program.

headline.main: 3 Borrowers Win Case on Eligibility for Public Service Loan Forgiveness
headline.print_headline: 3 Win Suit on Student Debt Forgiveness Program
